    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my civil eng exam. can you explain why we bother putting steel rebar inside concrete foundations? specifically what's the deal with the difference between how concrete handles compression vs how steel handles tension?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Concrete is strong in compression but weak in tension, meaning it cracks easily under pulling forces like wind or soil pressure. Steel rebar is placed inside to provide that missing tensile strength, allowing the foundation to withstand both pushing and pulling loads. When the concrete cracks due to tension, the steel takes the stress, preventing structural failure. This combination creates a composite material that is much stronger and more durable than either material alone.",
      "source": "target",
